WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Hi, I'm Garrett Grohlman, a professional educator at RStudio and the author of two books on R.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:18.000
I've put together these videos to teach you some of the main ideas of doing data wrangling with R and the Tidyverse.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:24.000
If you're not familiar with the Tidyverse, it's a collection of R packages that are designed to help you do data science.

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:31.000
In this series of short videos, we will walk through some of the most useful tools for wrangling your data with R.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:39.000
Also, keep in mind that you can skip around these videos to the tool that you want by clicking the jump to links in the video description.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:45.000
Normally when you wrangle your data, you have two goals.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:49.000
First, you might need to make your data set suitable to a particular piece of software.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:53.000
For example, we're going to need to make our data suitable to R because that's what we're using.

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:59.000
And then second, you can actually reveal information by changing the format and the structure of your data.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:03.000
Let's start with this first goal, making our data suitable for R.

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:10.000
So your data sets can come in many different formats, but there's one that R definitely prefers more than the others.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:15.000
And I have some toy data sets in this package, which I built on GitHub.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:18.000
You can download it if you want to use these data sets.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:22.000
It's completely not necessary. I'll be using these and you can just sit back and watch.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:27.000
But should you want to install this package, first install the DevTools package, which is on Crayon,

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:35.000
and then use the install GitHub command in DevTools to install this from the link rstudio-edawr.

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:40.000
Inside this data frame, inside this package, I have some data frames that are all fairly small,

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:46.000
but demonstrate the sort of layout and formatting issues that you might encounter with data in R.

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:51.000
For example, here are three data frames from the package.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:55.000
One's some data about hurricanes in the Atlantic Ocean.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:00.000
One's some cases of a disease, in this case TB, in different countries in different years.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:02.000
And one's some data about pollution.

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:06.000
And we could go through these three data frames and try to analyze what they contain.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:10.000
In particular, we could look at what variables are in each of the data frames.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:13.000
So in the storms data frame, it's pretty straightforward.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:16.000
We have a variable that talks about the names of each of our storms.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:21.000
A variable that has something to do with the wind. It's actually the maximum wind speed recorded for each storm.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:27.000
A variable that records the pressure of each storm and the date on which these measurements were made.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:30.000
So there's four variables in that data frame.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:36.000
If we turn our attention to the cases data frame, we'll see that we have a variable that has some sort of country code.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:40.000
So we see France, Deutschland, and the United States there.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:44.000
We have a variable that lists different years.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:47.000
2011, 2012, 2013.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:52.000
And we have a variable that's left over that's something like a frequency or a count.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:55.000
Or you might just call it N. And that's here.

00:02:55.000 --> 00:03:00.000
And if you compare cases to storms, you can see already that we have the difference between the two data frames.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:04.000
They store the values of their variables in different ways.

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:07.000
In storms, each variable is put in its own column.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:14.000
In cases, one variable's in a field of cells, one's across the column headers, and one's in its own column.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:18.000
When we get to pollution, we see a different format still.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:21.000
We have a variable that's different city names.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:27.000
And then it looks like we have a variable that describes particle size and a variable that describes some sort of amount.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:31.000
But I think you can also argue, and this is what I would argue,

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:37.000
that we actually have a variable which is the amount of large particles that each of these cities has in its air

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:41.000
and a second variable which is the amount of small particles that each city has in its air.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:46.000
And if you wanted to compute some number for each city, like the ratio of large to small particles,

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:50.000
then you'd have to treat these things as separate variables to do math with them.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:56.000
So we could look at this data frame as having three variables that are structured in a different way.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:00.000
So this is what I mean by data sets come in many different formats.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:06.000
But if you looked at how you'd pull the values of these different variables out of these data frames,

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:10.000
you'll see that one of these formats is much nicer with R code than others.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:15.000
In the storms data frame, you pull out each variable using the same syntax.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:19.000
The name of the data frame, dollar sign, the name of the column that you want.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:25.000
But if you want to pull out the values of, say, the count variable from cases,

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:29.000
you'd actually have to extract a bunch of cells and paste them together in some way.

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:31.000
Or the names of the columns would come together.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:34.000
When you move to pollution, you have to do something similar.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:40.000
And this is bad because when you write your code, you want to be able to make it as generalizable and as automated as possible.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:44.000
And if you have to stop and look at the data set that you're working with,

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:48.000
and then think about how to extract the values of the variable you want within that data set,

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:52.000
well, then it's going to be really hard to write a piece of code that will work with other data sets as well.

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:55.000
And the chance for making an error will be much greater.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:59.000
So just due to the way R works, its syntax structure and everything,

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:03.000
it's much easier to work with your data if each variable is in its own column.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:06.000
But there's other advantages as well.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:11.000
If we look at the storms data frame and consider making some sort of new variable,

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:16.000
in this case the ratio of pressure to wind, meteorologically I don't think that's a meaningful variable,

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:19.000
but this is similar to things you do with your own data.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:22.000
You'd use some math like this in R,

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:26.000
and what that code would do is it would first extract the pressure variable storms,

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:30.000
and then it would extract the wind variable, and then divide the two.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:35.000
And the way R operates is it's going to do element-wise operations.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:38.000
So instead of doing some sort of linear algebra thing here,

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:43.000
it's just going to pair up the first value of each vector, the second value, third value, and so on.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:46.000
And within those elements it will do the task of division.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:52.000
And so we get a vector that has, at the end, just as many values as the original vectors.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:57.000
Now this is great if you put your data in such a way that each variable is in its own column,

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:00.000
and then each row contains a single observation.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:05.000
Because what element-wise operations will do is it will make sure that the values of one observation

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:08.000
are only paired with other values from the same observation.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:11.000
Which as a data scientist is just what you want.

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:16.000
We wouldn't want to divide the pressure of Alberto by the wind speed of Alex.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:19.000
That's really not a meaning for the quantity.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:22.000
So we want to make sure we keep the pressure of Alberto with the wind of Alberto,

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:25.000
and the pressure of Alex with the wind of Alex, and so on.

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:28.000
Well, the structure of the storms data frame makes that happen automatically.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:32.000
It's taking advantage of R's element-wise operations.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:39.000
So that's sort of a roundabout way to say that there's one structure that just works well with the natural quirks of R,

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:43.000
and if you put your data into that structure before you begin to analyze your data,

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:47.000
you'll have a much quicker, more efficient experience when you work with that data.

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:51.000
And I'm going to call that data structure tidy data.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:57.000
This is a term invented by or popularized by Hadley, the author of Tidy R and Dplyr.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:06:59.000
And what it amounts to is you take your data,

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:05.000
and you make sure that each variable is saved in its own column, which we saw storms did.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:09.000
Make sure each observation is saved in its own row.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:17.000
I'm not going to go into what an observation is here, but it's both obvious and puzzling at the same time.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:23.000
And then finally, you want to put basically all the data that you plan to work with in the same data table

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:25.000
before you start working with it.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:29.000
Otherwise, you'll be recombining your data every time you make some sort of adjustment to it.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:36.000
So if you make your data tidy, with variables and columns, observations and rows,

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:41.000
and the type of data in its own table, it will be easy to access your variables,

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:45.000
and you'll automatically preserve observations as you do things to your data.

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:49.000
So that's sort of the goal. Tidy R is the means to get there.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:57.000
The package that picks up where reshape2 left off, if you are a user of reshape or reshape2,

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:03.000
and tidy R has two main functions, gather and spread, that do similar things as cast and melt

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:05.000
if you're coming from the reshape world.

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:08.000
And then there's several other functions we'll look at in there.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:11.000
But these are the main ones, and let's take a peek at them.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:17.000
So this is the cases data frame. This is how the variables were distributed.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:21.000
What I'd like you to do, and just for 30 seconds, because I can't really check in with you guys

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:26.000
or communicate with you, imagine how this data frame would look like if you restructured it

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:31.000
to be similar to storms, if it was tidy and had the variables country, year, and end.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:37.000
I think if you tried to scribble this out on a sheet of paper or something,

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:41.000
it would make it much easier to follow what gather does, which we'll look at in a second.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:02.000
Alright, so hopefully you had a chance to imagine what this data would look like in a different format.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:07.000
And this is what I propose this dataset would look like in a tidy format.

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:12.000
We want to keep all of the information in the dataset, and we want to keep the variables

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:13.000
that are there and the values that are there.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:17.000
We just want to restructure them so the variables each appear in their own column.

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:22.000
And we know that the columns we want to end up with are something like country, year, and end.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:28.000
And we can also look at the old dataset to determine what values need to go in which rows of the new dataset.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:36.000
We need to have some combination of France, the year 2011, and the end value for that combination needs to be 7,000.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:41.000
We also need a combination of Germany in 2011 with its own value.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:47.000
And basically we need to port over all the values in this field of cells into our new data frame.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:49.000
And when we're done, our data frame will look like this.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:53.000
So this is a tidy version of the case's data frame.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:58.000
Now it's very easy to pull out each of these variables by selecting the column name.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:04.000
And we can do this sort of thing with the gather function.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:08.000
And before we do it, we'll want to develop one piece of vocabulary.

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:17.000
So if you look at the output, you see it basically took the right-hand side of this data frame and turned it into two columns.

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:20.000
The first column is a key column.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:25.000
These are the names that these cells had in the previous data frame, the column names.

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:28.000
And we'll call the second column a value column.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:31.000
So these are actual values that appeared in that field of cells.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:34.000
And the idea of a key-value pair is actually pretty common.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:41.000
So we're going to use gather to take cells and turn it into just two columns, a key column and a value column.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:44.000
This is how the function works.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:47.000
This function comes with the TidyAR library.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:52.000
And you first give it the name of the data frame that you want to clean up.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:57.000
And then you give it the name that you want to use for the key column that results.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:00.000
And the name that you'll use for the value column.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:05.000
So we happen to be moving column names that were years into its own key column.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:10.000
And cell values that were n for frequency into their own column.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:14.000
But, you know, gather and TidyAR can't know what those things actually stand for.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:17.000
So here we get to tell them what to name the new columns.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:24.000
And then finally we just tell gather which of the columns we want it to use when it builds those final two columns.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:28.000
You may remember in the cases data frame, the first column was already tidy.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:30.000
The countries were already in their own column.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:32.000
So we don't include one in this index here.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:33.000
We leave one be.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:35.000
We just include two through four.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:37.000
Those were the columns that were not tidy.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:40.000
When you do this, your data will go from here to there.

