Yeah.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:39.000
Okay, so this is our pollutions data set.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:42.000
And it has three variables distributed like this.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:48.000
We can make this data set tidy with a column called city, a column called large, and a column called small.

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:51.000
Before we do, try to picture in your mind what that would look like.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:56.000
Which will help you understand the goal we're working towards in the next few slides.

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:06.000
Okay.

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:10.000
So the cases data frame look like rectangular data.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:17.000
That's the sort of data that you'll find very often when you only have a few variables and you want to display them in a format that fits in a paper pretty well.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:21.000
I don't know what to call this sort of data, but it exists quite often as well.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:27.000
And if you can switch this sort of data and rectangular data, you pretty much have full control over the format of your data frame.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:32.000
So here's the pollution data set as it is.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:35.000
And we want to make it a data frame that has these columns in it.

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:43.000
And just like before, it's only a matter of recreating the combinations that appear in the original data frame in our new data frame.

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:46.000
And when we do that, this is what the result looks like.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:48.000
See, it's tidy.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:50.000
It's more rectangular than the previous data frame.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:52.000
There's fewer rows.

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:54.000
We've removed some redundancy in here.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:59.000
Basically, we've made something that looks more like the cases data frame from before.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:06.000
When we did this operation, we again were working, you could think of it as working with a key column and a value column.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:12.000
The function that does this operation is called spread.

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:20.000
And what it does is it looks at the original data set and you give it a column to use as a key column and a column to use as a value column.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:23.000
And it'll use those columns to recreate a field of cells.

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:29.000
But the way you call spread is, the idea would be that the field of cells you recreate will be a tidy field of cells.

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:36.000
The syntax for spread is, you give it the data frame you want to reshape.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:40.000
You give it the name of the column to use as the key column in the original data.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:44.000
And the name of the column to use as the value column in the original data.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:45.000
Here, that's size and amount.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:48.000
And then it makes a transition for you.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:57.000
You could think of spread as taking data that's in a key value column format and putting it into a field of cells format or a rectangular table format.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:14:59.000
Whatever vocabulary you like.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:01.000
And you could think of gather as doing the opposite.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:11.000
And by going back and forth between gather and spread, you could actually move values into column names, out of column names, variables into a rectangular format, a tidy format.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:28.000
And since you don't have to apply spread or apply gather to the same columns each time, just by iterating between these two functions, you can take the same data, preserve all the combinations in the data, and make the layout very, very different than it was to begin with.

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:37.000
So the tidyR package also has two other functions that I think are useful, but not always going to be that useful.

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:43.000
If you looked at the STORMS dataset, and you're very persnickety, you might notice that it actually has three more variables in there.

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:47.000
You could extract a year variable from the date, a month variable, and a day variable.

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:51.000
And those variables are all combined into one column here, the date column.

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:59.000
What separate does is it takes a single column and it splits it up into multiple columns, based on some sort of separating character.

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:05.000
So this is really easy with dates, because dates normally have some sort of separator between year, month, and day.

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:13.000
And if we ran this code above here, we'd get a new data frame where the date column has been split into a year, month, and day, three columns.

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:18.000
If I save that as STORMS2, then I could use UNITE, which does the inverse.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:24.000
It takes several columns and puts them together in the same column, adding a separator between the values of the previous columns.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:29.000
So that's a great way to recreate some dates, although in this case those dates would be character strings.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:34.000
You need to reparse them if you want them to behave as dates in R, but that's another story.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:43.000
So just to recap about the tidyr package, it primarily works with the layout of your data and reshapes the layout.

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:49.000
You can use the gather function and the spread function to change the shapes back and forth.

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:53.000
They're complementary, and then you can use separate and unite to split up and unite columns.

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:55.000
They're also complementary.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:17:01.000
This package is designed basically to get data into that tidy format, which is the most efficient way to work with it in R.

